ion: ease-out;"><p data-path-to-node=3D"0">A <b data-path-to-node=3D"0" dat=
a-index-in-node=3D"2">Dependency-based parse tree</b> is a type of syntacti=
c structure that represents the grammatical relationships between words in =
a sentence through directed links. Unlike constituency-based trees (which f=
ocus on phrase structures like NP or VP), dependency trees focus on how wor=
ds relate to each other directly as <b data-path-to-node=3D"0" data-index-i=
n-node=3D"312">heads</b> and <b data-path-to-node=3D"0" data-index-in-node=
=3D"322">dependents</b>.</p><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"1">Core Concepts</h3><=
ul data-path-to-node=3D"2"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"2,0,0"><b data-path-=
to-node=3D"2,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Head and Dependent:</b> In every=
 relationship, one word acts as the <b data-path-to-node=3D"2,0,0" data-ind=
ex-in-node=3D"64">head</b> (the governor) and the other as the <b data-path=
-to-node=3D"2,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"105">dependent</b> (the modifier).=
 For example, in the phrase "big apple," "apple" is the head and "big" is t=
he dependent.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"2,1,0"><b data-path-to-no=
de=3D"2,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Root:</b> Every dependency tree h=
as a single <b data-path-to-node=3D"2,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"45">root</=
b> node, which is usually the main verb of the sentence and has no incoming=
 edges.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"2,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"=
2,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG):</b> A depende=
ncy tree is typically a DAG where each word has exactly one head, ensuring =
there are no cycles and every word is connected to the structure.</p></li><=
/ul><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"3">Key Characteristics</h3><ul data-path-to-no=
de=3D"4"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0" =
data-index-in-node=3D"0">Relationship Labels:</b> Each edge (the line betwe=
en words) is labeled with the specific grammatical relationship, such as <c=
ode data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"119">nsubj</code> (no=
minal subject), <code data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"144=
">obj</code> (direct object), or <code data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0" data-ind=
ex-in-node=3D"168">amod</code> (adjectival modifier).</p></li><li><p data-p=
ath-to-node=3D"4,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"4,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"=
0">Word-Centric:</b> There are no "phrasal" nodes (like "Noun Phrase"). The=
 nodes are the actual words of the sentence.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-no=
de=3D"4,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"4,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Projec=
tivity:</b> Most dependency trees are "projective," meaning the dependency =
lines do not cross when words are laid out in linear order, though "non-pro=
jective" structures occur in languages with very free word order.</p></li><=
/ul><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"5">Usage in NLP</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"6"=
>Dependency parsing is widely used in modern Natural Language Processing be=
cause it captures the <b data-path-to-node=3D"6" data-index-in-node=3D"96">=
semantic backbone</b> of a sentence:</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"7"><li><p =
data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0" data-index-in-no=
de=3D"0">Information Extraction:</b> It helps identify "who did what to who=
m" by following subject and object links.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=
=3D"7,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Efficien=
cy:</b> Dependency trees are often more compact and faster to compute than =
full phrase-structure trees.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"7,2,0"><b =
data-path-to-node=3D"7,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Cross-Linguistic Appli=
cability:</b> Because it focuses on functional relationships rather than ri=
gid word-order groupings, it works well for many different languages.</p></=
li></ul><p data-path-to-node=3D"8">Would you like to see a specific example=
 of how a sentence like <i data-path-to-node=3D"8" data-index-in-node=3D"64=
